  ## 11. PR-by-PR Merge Plan (Deployable Slices)

  1. PR-1: Slice 1 only.
  2. PR-2: Slice 2 read endpoints and schemas (entitlement-definitions GET/list + get by id).
  3. PR-3: Slice 2 mutations + dependency conflict mapping.
  4. PR-4: Slice 3 workspace payment-method mutations end-to-end.
  5. PR-5: Slice 4 migration + repository/service purchase adjustments.
  6. PR-6: Slice 4 console purchase routes/actions/controllers.
  7. PR-7: Slice 5 assignment/subscription list endpoints.
  8. PR-8: Slice 5 assignment/subscription mutation endpoints.
  9. PR-9: Slice 6 provider contract + Stripe implementation.
  10. PR-10: Slice 6 Paddle explicit 501 and contract tests.
  11. PR-11: Slice 7 assistant tool metadata + tests.
  12. PR-12: Slice 8 API clients + console/workspace UI + docs + final test sweep.

  ———

  ## 12. Validation Sequence

  Run this exact sequence at the end of each major merge window:

  1. npm --prefix ../.. run lint:architecture:client
  2. npm --prefix ../.. run test:architecture:client
  3. npm --prefix ../.. run test:architecture:shared-ui
  4. npm run lint
  5. npm run test
  6. npm run test:client
  7. npm run docs:api-contracts:check
  8. npm run test -- billing

  ———

  ## 13. High-Risk Points To Watch

  1. Action ID drift between ACTION_IDS, controller constants, and contributor definitions.
  2. Console service dependency wiring if contributor method requirements expand.
  3. FK conflict handling on delete paths returning raw DB errors instead of mapped 409 contracts.
  4. Provider capability mismatch causing partial behavior divergence across Stripe/Paddle.
  5. Assistant console-surface gap if transport expansion is not shipped with tool metadata.
